## O'Shea Leading Indicator Overlay (added 2026-03-26)

`detect_market_regime()` now applies a forward-looking stress score on top of the lagging SPY/VIX signals. This catches regime deterioration **1–2 weeks earlier** than the 200 SMA alone.

Three leading signals are combined into a composite stress score (0.0 = calm → 1.0 = severe):

| Signal | What it measures | Stressed when |
|---|---|---|
| VIX term structure | VIX9D vs VIX30 spread | Front month > back month (inverted) |
| Credit spread proxy | HYG vs IEF 30-day return | HY bonds falling while treasuries flat |
| Market breadth | % of large-cap proxies above 50-day MA | < 50% of large caps above 50-day |

**Downgrade thresholds:**

| Stress score | Base regime → Adjusted |
|---|---|
| ≥ 0.85 | Any → `UNFAVORABLE` |
| ≥ 0.75 | CHOPPY/MIXED → `STRONG_DOWNTREND` |
| ≥ 0.60 | STRONG_UPTREND → `MIXED` |
| ≥ 0.60 | CHOPPY → `MIXED` |

A Telegram alert fires whenever a leading-indicator downgrade occurs.

**To bypass the overlay:** pass `use_leading_indicators=False` to `detect_market_regime()` (e.g., in unit tests or when yfinance is rate-limited).

**Current stress score as of 2026-03-26:** ~0.57 (below the 0.60 downgrade threshold).

## L1 Execution Regime — How Each Is Set

`regime_detector.py → detect_market_regime()` classifies SPY vs 200 SMA + VIX (with leading indicator overlay):

| Condition | L1 Regime |
|---|---|
| VIX > 30, price within 1% of 200 SMA, optional 20d vol > 2% | `UNFAVORABLE` |
| Price < 200 SMA by > 2% AND VIX > 20 | `STRONG_DOWNTREND` |
| Price > 200 SMA by > 2%, VIX < 18, ≥3 days above 200, EMA8/21 > 200 | `STRONG_UPTREND` |
| Price < 200 SMA by > 2% AND VIX < 20 | `MIXED` |
| All other conditions | `CHOPPY` (default) |

Written to `logs/regime_context.json` via `persist_regime_to_context()`. L2 band labels (`RISK_ON`, etc.) must never be written to this file — see `080-regime-context-integrity.mdc`.

